e author argues that even in such a vast realm, knowledge was built locally by people who existed at the peripheries of empire. Organized along routes and centralized into local nodes, peripheral knowledge accumulated in regional centers before moving on to the heart of the empire in Spain. The study takes the Kingdom of Guatemala as its departure point and examines the related aspects of documents and distance in three sections: part one looks at document genre, and how the creation of documents was shaped by distance; part two looks at the movement of documents and the workings of the mail system; part three looks at document storage and how archives played an essential part in the flow of paper.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCentral-local government relationsxColoniesxSpain. 0aCentral-local government relationsxColonieszSpain. 0aGeographical perceptionxColoniesxSpain. 0aGeographical perceptionxColonieszSpain. 0aGovernment publicationsxColoniesxSpain. 0aGovernment publicationsxColonieszSpain. 0aGovernment publicationsxHistoryxCentral America. 0aGovernment publicationszCentral AmericaxHistory. 4aDistance. 4aGuatemala. 4aSpanish empire. 4aarchives. 4adocuments. 4amail. 4aperipheries. 4aroutes. 4aspace. 4atravel. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804788823zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788823423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804788823.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles